When that King came to Face the Prince of <HI>Orange</HI> at <HI>Salisbury,</HI> they all for&s;ook him, and fir&s;t or la&s;t went over to his Enemy.</NOTE> <HI>The Tribe of</HI> Life and Fortune, Loyalty:</L>
<L><PB N="18" REF="143">
The <HI>Stand-by Men,</HI> the Old<NOTE N="a" PLACE="foot"><HI>Abhoring Race,</HI> taken from the Famous Addre&s;&s;es for abhoring Pe|tioning in the Time of King <HI>Charles</HI> the Second, when the Subjects being injur'd, Petition'd for redre&s;s of their Grievances; and the&s;e Gentle|men addre&s;s'd the King on the contrary, applauded his Oppre&s;&s;ions, and declar'd them&s;elves to be Abhorrers of Petitioning.</NOTE> <HI>Abhorring</HI> Race,</L>
<L>Who had no Courage, 'cau&s;e they had no Grace;</L>
